## Branch Purpose

This branch keeps the `zclaw` ESP-IDF experiment in the same repository without touching the long-lived Arduino mainline flow.

Branch name:

`codex/zclaw-esp32-try`

The goal of this branch is to run a phone-first `zclaw` device on a classic ESP32 with:

- AP provisioning on first boot or recovery
- local web chat over Wi-Fi
- `POST + SSE` chat transport
- DHT11 temperature/humidity tool support
- 0.91 inch OLED status display
- PowerShell helpers for Windows build and flash

## Repository Areas That Matter

- Firmware source: `vendor/zclaw_upstream/`
- Windows helper scripts: `scripts/`
- Branch notes and setup guide: `docs/zclaw-esp32-try.md`

`vendor/zclaw_upstream` is vendored source. Its original nested Git metadata was moved aside on purpose so this branch can track the files from the main repository:

- hidden backup path: `vendor/zclaw_upstream/.git.vendor_backup/`

Do not rename that backup folder back to `.git` unless you intentionally want `vendor/zclaw_upstream` to become a nested repository again.

## Hardware Assumptions In This Branch

This branch was developed and tested around the following hardware layout:

- Board: classic ESP32 dev board with CP210x USB-UART
- Sensor: DHT11 module
- DHT11 data pin: `GPIO5`
- OLED: 0.91 inch I2C OLED, SSD1306-compatible, usually `128x32`
- OLED SDA: `GPIO21`
- OLED SCL: `GPIO22`
- OLED address: `0x3C`

Expected OLED pins:

- `GND -> GND`
- `VCC -> 3.3V`
- `SCL -> GPIO22`
- `SDA -> GPIO21`

Expected DHT11 pins:

- `VCC -> 3.3V`
- `GND -> GND`
- `DATA -> GPIO5`

## Firmware Behavior In This Branch

The device now works like a standalone Wi-Fi product instead of a serial-only demo.

Provisioning mode:

- starts a setup AP when Wi-Fi is missing or recovery is requested
- serves a normal HTTP setup page
- setup address is `http://192.168.4.1`

Chat mode:

- joins the configured Wi-Fi by DHCP
- serves the local chat page on the device IP
- uses `POST /api/chat` plus SSE stream updates

Recovery paths:

- Boot button long press enters setup mode
- Wi-Fi failure can fall back to setup AP
- setup and LLM settings are split instead of forced into one save action

OLED role:

- shows short boot and setup guidance
- shows current DHCP IP during chat mode
- keeps messages short enough for a `128x32` display

## Windows Development Environment

This branch assumes Windows PowerShell and ESP-IDF installed under:

- `C:\Espressif\frameworks\esp-idf-v5.5.3`

Important environment values used on this machine:

- `IDF_PATH=C:\Espressif\frameworks\esp-idf-v5.5.3`
- `IDF_TOOLS_PATH=C:\Espressif`
- `IDF_PYTHON_ENV_PATH=C:\Espressif\python_env\idf5.5_py3.11_env`

USB serial during development was usually:

- `COM5`

If your machine or board differs, update the script parameters instead of hardcoding local paths into source files.

## Helper Scripts

Useful PowerShell helpers:

- `scripts/zclaw-sync.ps1`
- `scripts/zclaw-build.ps1`
- `scripts/zclaw-flash.ps1`
- `scripts/zclaw-provision.ps1`

Typical classic ESP32 workflow:

```powershell
.\scripts\zclaw-sync.ps1
.\scripts\zclaw-build.ps1 -Target esp32
.\scripts\zclaw-flash.ps1 -Target esp32 -Port COM5
```

If you are using a different chip:

- `ESP32-S3`: use `-Target esp32s3`
- `ESP32-C3`: use `-Target esp32c3`

## Secrets And Local Files

These files are intentionally ignored and should stay local:

- `.zclaw_web_api_key`

Do not commit live Wi-Fi credentials or API keys.

## What Future Developers Need To Adapt

### 1. Board target

Check the actual MCU before building.

- classic ESP32 and ESP32-S3 do not use the same target
- adjust `idf.py set-target` or the `-Target` argument in the scripts

### 2. USB-UART and flash port

If the board does not enumerate as `COM5`, change only the script argument:

```powershell
.\scripts\zclaw-flash.ps1 -Target esp32 -Port COM7
```

### 3. Wi-Fi and LLM settings

This branch separates network configuration from AI configuration.

If you change provider behavior:

- keep the setup page fields split into Wi-Fi and AI sections
- keep base URL handling tolerant, for example allowing `https://api.deepseek.com/v1`
- resolve provider-specific chat endpoints inside firmware instead of asking users to type the full path every time

### 4. Sensor changes

Current sensor support expects a DHT11 on `GPIO5`.

If you move or replace the sensor:

- update the GPIO constant and tool description
- retest the local `/dht` path and the chat-triggered tool path
- if switching to DHT22 or another sensor family, review timing and cache behavior instead of reusing DHT11 assumptions blindly

### 5. OLED changes

The UI for the physical display was designed for a very small `0.91 inch 128x32` screen.

If you change the display:

- keep lines short on `128x32`
- retune page rotation and font size if moving to `128x64`
- confirm the I2C address instead of assuming `0x3C`
- if OLED is removed entirely, make sure setup guidance is still clear through the web UI alone

### 6. Upstream zclaw updates

If you want newer upstream `zclaw` code:

- review local changes in `vendor/zclaw_upstream/main/` carefully before replacing files
- expect conflicts in `web_ui.c`, `main.c`, `llm.c`, `agent.c`, `oled_display.c`, and sensor-related files
- keep the branch behavior goals intact: AP provisioning, local chat, SSE streaming, DHT11 tool, OLED guidance

### 7. Browser UI expectations

The mobile web UI was intentionally simplified so chat remains the primary screen.

If you redesign it:

- keep chat as the first-class surface
- keep settings secondary
- avoid putting all controls on the home screen
- validate on an actual phone, not only a desktop browser

## Recommended First Steps For A New Developer

1. Verify ESP-IDF works from a fresh PowerShell window.
2. Build for the correct target with `scripts/zclaw-build.ps1`.
3. Flash the board and confirm the setup AP appears.
4. Complete Wi-Fi and AI setup from a phone.
5. Open the local chat page from the device DHCP IP.
6. Confirm DHT11 and OLED behavior on real hardware.

## Current Branch Intent

This branch is meant to stay alive as an experimental integration branch.

Do not treat it like a short-lived PR branch unless the owner asks for that later.
